content.description: Near the left side of the north face is a varnished right facing corner with an RP crack.  It soon widens and leads to a small ledge.  Go left on the ledge to a crack that leads to the top.  Excellent rock.

climbs.name: Love Goat, The
climbs.fa: Craig Fry and Dave Evans, April 1986

content.description: Tricky, shallow flared hand jams continue for a surprising number of moves.  The protection is good, and this route is worth doing.
content.location: This is the next crack to the right of Poaching Bighorn.  It's a continuous crack from bottom to top of the rock.

climbs.name: Jack in the Crack
climbs.fa: Don Wilson, Karen Wilson, Jack Marshall  1987

content.description:
This is a short, left curving finger crack on the east face of the Bighorn Dome summit block, right above Greenhorn Dihedral.

It looks casual, but it's got spank written all over it...
content.protection: A few nuts and thin cams to 2", mainly finger size.  Gear anchor - small tcu's work.
content.location:
Located on the summit block's east face at the top of Greenhorn Dihedral.

Descent: Walk off back to the top of Greenhorn Dihedral.

climbs.name: Greenhorn Dihedral
climbs.fa: Craig Fry, Dave Evans, Kelly Carignan, Margy Floyd & Alan Roberts 2/85

content.description: Toward the middle of the north face is a right facing corner with green lichen on its right wall.  It goes over a small roof higher.  3 out of 5 stars.

This route begins just left of Greehorn Dihedral on a protruding narrow rectangular block. Climb past three bolts using edges on the face as well as the arete on both sides of the block to a small roof. Ascend the roof into a thin crack that ends on a ledge. The rock is somewhat grainy to the roof but solid once the thin crack is reached. Two out of five stars.
content.protection: Mostly small/ medium TCU's, cams, and stoppers plus quick draws for three 1/4" bolts and one piton. An anchor can be set up where the route converges with "Greenhorn Dihedral."
